{"type":"freeform","cover":{"titleText":"","subTitleText":"","presenterText":"","dateText":"","logos":[]},"section":{"sectionText":"","smallerSectionText":""},"freeform":{"content":[[{"type":"text","span":3,"markdown":"In 2025, the largest ANC1 volume occurred in January, with approximately 90,000 visits. For ANC4, the highest volume was observed in April 2025, at nearly 80,000 visits.

On average, ANC4 volumes are about 10,000 visits lower than ANC1 — indicating that roughly 10–12% fewer women progress to their fourth antenatal visit compared to the first.

Addressing the gap between the first and fourth visits remains critical to ensuring continuity of care and improved antenatal outcomes.","stretch":true,"fillArea":true,"textSize":1,"textBackground":"grey","placeholderInvisible":false,"placeholderStretch":true,"placeholderHeight":50,"useFigureAdditionalScale":false,"figureAdditionalScale":1,"imgHeight":300,"imgFit":"inside","imgStretch":true,"hideFigureCaption":false,"hideFigureSubCaption":false,"hideFigureFootnote":false},{"type":"figure","presentationObjectInReportInfo":{"id":"a498647a-a47c-449d-a1b8-4f2814b85152","moduleId":"m003","isDefault":false,"selectedReplicantValue":""},"stretch":true,"fillArea":false,"textSize":1,"textBackground":"none","placeholderInvisible":false,"placeholderStretch":true,"placeholderHeight":50,"useFigureAdditionalScale":true,"figureAdditionalScale":1,"imgHeight":300,"imgFit":"inside","imgStretch":true,"hideFigureCaption":false,"hideFigureSubCaption":false,"hideFigureFootnote":false}]],"useHeader":true,"headerText":"Trends in antenatal care","useFooter":false,"footerText":""}}

{"type":"freeform","cover":{"titleText":"","subTitleText":"","presenterText":"","dateText":"","logos":[]},"section":{"sectionText":"","smallerSectionText":""},"freeform":{"content":[[{"type":"text","stretch":true,"fillArea":true,"textSize":1,"textBackground":"grey","placeholderInvisible":false,"useFigureAdditionalScale":false,"figureAdditionalScale":1,"span":4,"markdown":"In 2025, deliveries, postnatal care, and early breastfeeding services remained aligned with expected levels and have similar service volumes, showing stable continuity in maternal–newborn care.

While all three indicators show similar trends in 2025, on average, maternal PNC1 is about 7 % lower and early breastfeeding about 10–12 % lower than deliveries, underscoring a modest continuity gap after childbirth.
